============================================================
STEM: Either John or his sisters ___ the kitchen before they go to school.
  (1) clean
  (2) cleans
  (3) has cleaned
  (4) have cleaned
ANSWER: 1

ELABORATION (684 chars):
This question tests **subject-verb agreement** when using **either... or**.

When subjects are joined by **either... or**, the verb must agree with the subject closest to it. Here, the closest subject is the plural noun **sisters**, so we need the plural present tense verb **clean** to show a regular daily routine.

Here is why the other options fail:
**(2) cleans**: Mismatched subject; this is a singular verb, but **sisters** is plural.
**(3) has cleaned**: Mismatched subject and wrong tense; it is a singular verb used for completed actions, not habits.
**(4) have cleaned**: Wrong tense; the present perfect tense does not fit a simple daily habit like cleaning before school.

